The residential school system in Canada removed Indigenous children from
their families with the aim of suppressing their history and culture to
assimilate them into the dominant Canadian culture. The last school closed
in the late 1990s. The story of Chanie Wenjack, a 12-year-old Anishinaabe
boy who died after running away from a school in northern Ontario in
1966, illustrates the gravity of the treatment of Indigenous children, which
has left deep scars on communities to this day.
Inspired by Chanieâ€™s story, the Gord Downie & Chanie Wenjack Fund
(DWF) aims to build cultural understanding and create a path toward
reconciliation between Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples.
Meaningful actions contribute to reaching reconciliation, referred to here
as reconciliACTIONs*. The reconciliation journey is made up of different
steps, where participant contributions range from getting informed
through newsletters to volunteering as part of youth and legacy programs.
As such, different stages are necessary to building awareness, education
and connections between peoples in Canada.
Data source: DWF Data on reconciliACTIONs (2021-2023)
